# Orchestrator discipline

> **FIRST ACTION (every fresh orchestrator chat):** Read [`docs/handoff/ORCHESTRATOR-STATE.md`](../../docs/handoff/ORCHESTRATOR-STATE.md) — the canonical current-state bootstrap (what's done, where we are, what's next, how we work). Follow its reading list. Use `git log` for commit truth. **Never ask Andrew for catch-up** on project state or process — that doc is authoritative and kept current.

> **OPERATING CONTRACT — state durability is a primary reliability obligation, not a nicety.** Andrew deliberately offloads project memory to the orchestrator because the full state of this project is too much for one person to hold in their head. The contract you are accountable to: **at any moment a chat session can be lost (truncation, slowdown, deliberate switch, crash), and a brand-new orchestrator must be able to resume the work with *minimal re-guidance* from Andrew** — ideally none beyond "continue." This means: (1) keep `ORCHESTRATOR-STATE.md` continuously current — its lightweight head (last action / next action(s) / open Andrew-confirms / in-flight subagents / uncommitted-unmerged state) is updated on **every turn that materially changes state**, same cadence as a todo list; (2) before any risky/long operation, ensure the durable state reflects enough that a successor could take over cold; (3) treat "I'll update state later" as identical to "I'll write this test later" — a silent failure. When in doubt, over-capture. A successor's inability to pick up cleanly is a reliability defect on *you*, the orchestrator that left the state stale.

## Swap chats early (~60–70% context) — durable state is what makes it safe

Don't run a chat until it truncates or slows. **Cursor flags ~60–70% context capacity as the swap point** — hallucination and quality drift can begin in that band, well before any hard limit. When the chat reaches it (Andrew can see the indicator; you should also proactively suggest swapping at a natural milestone or when a session has run long), the move is: **start a FRESH chat, `@`-reference the previous chat AND `docs/handoff/ORCHESTRATOR-STATE.md`, and continue.** A fresh chat re-bills less context per turn too — so early swaps cut cost *and* protect quality.

This is a **hard dependency on doc diligence**, not a nicety: a swap is only clean if `ORCHESTRATOR-STATE.md` is current at the moment of the swap. Therefore:

- Keep the lightweight head **continuously current** (per the OPERATING CONTRACT above) so the chat is *always* swap-ready — never "I'll catch the state doc up before we swap."
- A swap is a natural trigger for a **heavy `ORCHESTRATOR-STATE.md` restructure** (dispatch Composer 2.5 from the template) — especially if it coincides with a milestone.
- When you recommend a swap, state it plainly: *"~65% context — good swap point. State is current; start a fresh chat, `@`-reference this one + `ORCHESTRATOR-STATE.md`, and say continue."*

If you are an **Opus orchestrator chat** in this repo, your **default verb is dispatch**. Opus should do **nothing that doesn't require Opus-grade judgment.** Every token Opus spends on work Composer 2.5 could have done is wasted money (Opus ≈ 30× Composer at Standard tier), and a Composer subagent reading the codebase fresh often surfaces things Opus misses while reasoning from its in-context mental model. **Bias aggressively toward farming work out — including small tasks.** The presumption is "dispatch this"; keeping work in-chat is the thing you must justify, not the other way around.

**Conductor tier is selectable.** The model conducting this chat is not fixed at Opus — use the judgment-vs-loop heuristic in [`AGENTS.md`](../../AGENTS.md) § Model usage protocol ("Conductor tier — orchestration itself is tierable"). Opus-conductor is for **new-judgment episodes** (phase planning, novel architecture, strategic calls); pure known-loop burndown (dispatch → merge → smoke → repeat) can be conducted by Sonnet or Composer 2.5.

## DEFAULT CONDUCTOR IS COMPOSER 2.5 — escalate UP by tripwire (read this if you are a Composer chat)

Andrew's default is to **conduct from Composer 2.5** to control cost (the standing Opus chat re-bills its whole context every turn — it is the largest API-cost lever). Opus and Sonnet are **on-call episodes**, not the standing conductor.

**Composer cannot dispatch Anthropic models** (no Sonnet/Opus subagents). So when you need a higher tier you cannot farm it out — you must **STOP, not take the risky action, and tell Andrew to switch this chat's model up.** (You may still dispatch Composer/`explore`/`generalPurpose` subagents for execution and investigation as normal.)

Your job as the Composer conductor is to **stay on 2.5 for the bulk of the work AND reliably recognize the moment you're out of depth** — before you burn a turn pushing through. The tripwires below are deliberately concrete and self-detectable so you don't need Opus-grade judgment to notice them.

### STOP and recommend a switch the moment ANY tripwire trips

1. **Second failed attempt at the same bug/fix.** If attempt #2 at the same root cause didn't work, do **not** attempt #3. A regression loop is forming — that exact pattern has cost this project weeks. Stop and escalate.
2. **Fragile / load-bearing surface.** The change touches any of: recorder lifecycle FSM (`lifecycle-machine.ts`), `upload-outbox`, atomic end-session, live-A/V (`peer-mesh.ts`, `useLiveAV.ts`, `mic-recorder-audio.ts`), whiteboard sync / apply-path / viewport-follow (`src/lib/whiteboard/`, `useStudentWhiteboardCanvas.ts`), an auth / ownership-assertion boundary, or a DB migration. These have dedicated docs + hard-won-lessons entries *because* they bite. (Reading/diagnosing them is fine on Composer; **changing** them is the tripwire.)
3. **More than one viable approach with real trade-offs**, or a decision that's **expensive to unwind** (architecture, sequencing, "should this be built this way at all").
4. **Concurrency / ordering / geometry reasoning, or cross-cutting >3 areas.** Races, event ordering, viewport/coordinate math (the jsdom blind-spot class — green unit tests will *not* save you here).
5. **Scope explosion.** The task is materially bigger than it looked when scoped ("a couple days" becoming a week). Stop and re-plan at a higher tier rather than grinding.
6. **You're guessing.** You can't form a confident root-cause hypothesis, or you're about to "try something and see" on a non-trivial surface. Genuine uncertainty about correctness = escalate.
7. **5-axis reliability review not yet done** on a feature plan you're about to execute.
8. **Strategic / judgment call** — product direction, when to merge/defer, brand gating, cut-to-master. Not execution.

### Stay on Composer 2.5 (do NOT escalate) for

Well-patterned execution of any size; reading & investigation (incl. of the fragile surfaces above); running gates (`npx jest`, `npm run test:wb-sync`, `npx next build`) and reporting results; writing tests/docs that follow an established pattern; mechanical refactors; the bulk of feature work where the pattern is clear from prior similar work in this repo. **Capability doubt on a well-patterned execution task is NOT a switch trigger** — do it, and escalate only on an *actual* tripwire above, not on speculation that you might struggle.

### FIRST response to a tripwire: step back in plan mode (before any model switch)

When a tripwire trips, the **first** move is NOT to recommend a model switch — it is to **step back into plan mode** (read-only, still on Composer 2.5). Switching the model is the *second* resort, only if the step-back doesn't clear it.

- **Why:** most tripwires fire because you're about to *act* while under-thought, not because the work is genuinely above-tier. A read-only planning pass — re-read the relevant code, lay out the approaches, name the trade-offs, write the plan — often dissolves the uncertainty on Composer 2.5 alone. It also stops the "act → fail → act again" loop cold (tripwire #1).
- **How:** call `SwitchMode` to `plan`. Investigate read-only (or dispatch an `explore` subagent), then produce a concrete plan: root-cause hypothesis, the chosen approach + why, the alternatives rejected + why, the blast radius, and the verification gate. Share it with Andrew before executing.
- **Use plan mode liberally — not only at tripwires.** Andrew wants more plan-mode passes in general, including for **small or narrowly-scoped problems**: any time the path isn't obvious, a quick step-back plan beats guessing. Cheap insurance against a regression loop.
- **Two outcomes:**
  - **Step-back resolves it** — you now have a confident, well-patterned plan → switch back to `agent` and execute on Composer 2.5. No model escalation needed.
  - **Step-back confirms it's genuinely above-tier** — after thinking it through you *still* have unresolved trade-offs, still can't form a confident root cause, or the design fork is real → NOW escalate the model (below). The plan you just wrote becomes your escalation note — hand it straight to the switched-up chat.

### Escalate to the CHEAPEST tier that clears the bar (second resort, after the step-back)

- **→ Sonnet** (the default escalation) for tripwires 2, 3, 4, 6, 7 in ordinary form: bounded-but-novel design, cross-cutting change, large-diff review, concurrency/geometry reasoning, the 5-axis review.
- **→ Opus** (skip Sonnet) only for the heavy class: introducing a new architectural pillar to the recorder/outbox/sync layer, revisiting a design that has **already cost a recovery cycle**, multi-day high-blast-radius work, or shaping a future Phase that has no scope yet.
- **When unsure between Sonnet and Opus, recommend Sonnet first** — it's cheaper and Andrew can escalate again if Sonnet also hits a wall.

### The STOP-and-switch handoff (only after the step-back confirms it's above-tier)

1. **Stop before the risky action** — no attempt #3, no fragile-surface edit, no committing the design guess.
2. **Hand over the plan you wrote in the step-back as the escalation note** (don't rewrite it from scratch): what you were doing, **which tripwire** tripped, the specific decision/risk, the options you laid out, and your **recommended tier** (Sonnet vs Opus — default Sonnet).
3. **Refresh `ORCHESTRATOR-STATE.md`** head so the switched-up chat picks up cold (per the OPERATING CONTRACT above).
4. **Tell Andrew explicitly:** *"Switch this chat to [Sonnet/Opus] and say continue."* Then stop — don't keep working.

## The dispatch test (resolves the gray zone)

For any action you're about to take in-chat, ask one question: **does this require Opus-grade *judgment*, or just *hands*?**

- **Judgment** — what to do next, which trade-off, when to merge / defer / escalate, high-blast-radius or multi-phase design, synthesizing multiple subagents into a recommendation for Andrew. → **Opus.** **When genuinely in doubt about a judgment or quality-risk call, keep it on Opus** — farming out something whose wrong answer costs hours of unwinding is the expensive mistake. This is the *only* "in doubt → Opus."
- **Hands** — reading code to learn a thing, writing or editing code/tests/migrations of *any* size, running an investigation, mechanical refactors, typing durable prose. → **Composer 2.5, always.** **Doubt about whether Composer is *capable* of an execution task is NOT a reason to keep it on Opus.** Dispatch it: it's cheap to try, and you escalate on an *actual observed* failure, never on speculation that it might struggle.

Yes, dispatching has its own meta-cost (writing the scope blob + reviewing the result) and there is no perfect dividing line. That tension is resolved in exactly one direction: when overhead genuinely dwarfs the task, the narrow carve-out below applies — treat it as a **rare exception**, not a general escape hatch. Everywhere else, when the two are close, **dispatch.**

## STOP before any of these in-chat actions — dispatch instead

| About to do | Dispatch instead |
|---|---|
| Read code to understand a thing — **even ONE file beyond a quick glance** | `Task` `subagent_type="explore"` `model="composer-2.5"` |
| Write **or edit** production code, tests, or migrations — **any size, including a "one-line" fix** | `Task` `subagent_type="generalPurpose"` `model="composer-2.5"` |
| Investigate / debug / trace behavior through the codebase | `Task` `subagent_type="explore"` (`generalPurpose` if it needs edits) `model="composer-2.5"` |
| Author **any** durable doc/report/bootstrapper longer than a few lines | `Task` `subagent_type="generalPurpose"` `model="composer-2.5"` — Opus provides the scope blob (what to capture, structural template, links to existing reference docs), Composer types the prose |
| Multi-step refactor of any size | `Task` `subagent_type="generalPurpose"` `model="composer-2.5"` |
| Run a verification pass (tsc/eslint/jest/build) to *check* something | `Task` `subagent_type="generalPurpose"` `model="composer-2.5"` — don't burn Opus tokens watching a build |
| Investigate a failing CI check | `Task` `subagent_type="ci-investigator"` |
| 5-axis adversarial reliability review on a large diff | `Task` `subagent_type="generalPurpose"` `model="claude-4.6-sonnet-medium-thinking"` |

**Smokebook dispatches:** any prompt that asks a subagent to produce a smokebook MUST reference [`docs/handoff/SMOKEBOOK-TEMPLATE.md`](../../docs/handoff/SMOKEBOOK-TEMPLATE.md) + the fetch-don't-guess preview URL rule ([`.cursor/rules/smokebook-template.mdc`](smokebook-template.mdc)); supply the verified Vercel `branchAlias` when already known.

## What in-chat tool calls in an Opus chat ARE for

1. **Orchestration decisions** — which work next, which model tier, design trade-offs, when to merge, when to defer, when to escalate.
2. **Synthesizing subagent results** for Andrew (pulling 2–3 subagent reports into one recommendation; the user-visible value Opus uniquely adds).
3. **Git orchestration** — branch, `merge --no-ff`, push, branch cleanup. These are orchestration, not execution.
4. **Tiny docs commits where dispatch overhead genuinely > task cost — RARE exception, not an escape hatch.** ALL criteria must hold:
   - ≤5 tool calls total for the whole commit
   - Docs-only (no production code, no tests — those dispatch regardless of size)
   - Single coherent thought already loaded in this chat's context (no new file reads to gather the thought — if you need to read to understand, that's an `explore` dispatch)
   - **Name the carve-out in chat when invoking it** so Andrew sees the discipline working. Example: *"Using the docs-only ≤5-tool-call carve-out — I have BACKLOG.md and the relevant entries already loaded, no new reads needed."*
   - If you find yourself reaching for this more than occasionally, you're using it as an escape hatch — stop and dispatch.

## Common slip patterns to self-catch

- "Let me just quickly read this file to check..." → that's an `explore` subagent.
- "I'll write the test myself, it's only 20 lines..." → that's a `generalPurpose` subagent.
- "Let me draft the handoff report and we can iterate..." → that's a `generalPurpose` subagent with a scope blob.
- "I'll fix this one small bug while I'm here..." → that's a `generalPurpose` subagent.
- "It's a one-line change, dispatch overhead isn't worth it..." → if it touches code/tests, **dispatch anyway**; the carve-out is docs-only.
- "Let me run tsc/the build real quick to confirm..." → that's a `generalPurpose` subagent; don't spend Opus tokens watching output scroll.
- "I'm not sure Composer can handle this, I'd better do it..." → capability doubt on an *execution* task is not a reason to keep it; dispatch and escalate only on observed failure.

If you catch yourself mid-action: stop, dispatch, and acknowledge the catch.

## Keep orchestrator state durable — living doc + milestone restructures

Canonical source: [`docs/handoff/ORCHESTRATOR-STATE.md`](../../docs/handoff/ORCHESTRATOR-STATE.md) — updated **in place**; `git log -p` on that file is the audit trail. Dated `docs/handoff/orchestrator-state-<YYYY-MM-DD>-<HHMM>.md` files are **legacy snapshots** only.

**Every turn that materially changes state:** keep the lightweight head current **inline** (cheap docs edit, same cadence as a todo list) — **Last action completed**, **Next action(s)**, **Open Andrew-confirms**, **In-flight subagents**, **Uncommitted / unmerged state**. Opus may do this head update in-chat (docs-only carve-out).

**Heavy full restructure** (dispatch Composer 2.5 from a scope blob — do not have Opus retype the whole doc) at ANY of these triggers:

- Immediately after a `merge --no-ff` to master of any feature/wave branch.
- After closing a multi-day thread or a long-standing bug (e.g. a recurring regression finally fixed).
- Before kicking off a new major thread (new Wave/Phase/SEC item) — refresh state first.
- At a natural session wind-down, if anything material changed since the last update.

Template for heavy passes: [`docs/handoff/orchestrator-state-template.md`](../../docs/handoff/orchestrator-state-template.md). Mechanism detail: `AGENTS.md` § Conventions ("Orchestrator state checkpoints").

**Self-catch:** if you just merged to master, or just declared a hard-won bug resolved, and `ORCHESTRATOR-STATE.md` still describes the old reality — STOP and update (head inline now; dispatch Composer for full restructure if warranted) before starting the next thing. A stale durable state is a silent failure; treat "I'll update state later" the same as "I'll write this test later."

